FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE (SUSPECTED), CATTLE, JAPAN (02)
****************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
See Also
Foot & mouth disease, suspected - Japan & S. Korea 20000328234118
Foot & mouth disease suspected, cattle - Japan 20000327214606
Date: Tue, 28 Mar 2000 21:56:20 +0900
From: ponpoco <dolphin@mail.ne.jp>
Source: National Institute of Animal Health (Japan)
<http://ss.niah.affrc.go.jp/FMD/report-oie.html>

Animal Health Emergency Report (suspicion)
Report date: 24 Mar 2000
Country : Japan
Name of sender: Kenichi Matsubara
Position: Director of Animal Health Division,
Ministry of Agriculture Forestry and Fisheries
e-mail: toshiyuki-tsutsui@nm.maff.go.jp
Tokyo, 100
Disease Name: Foot and Mouth Disease (suspicion)
Code: A 001
Nature of diagnosis: clinical and laboratory.
Date of Initial detection of animal health Incident: 8 Mar 2000
Location: Miyazki city, Miyazaki Prefecture
No. of outbreaks: 1
Total number of animals in the outbreak
Species Code: bov
Susceptible: 10
Cases: 10
Deaths: 0
Destroyed: 10
Slaughtered: 0
Diagnosis:
10 cattle were clinically suspected to be infected with FMD. Samples were
taken by veterinary officers of Miyazaki Livestock Hygiene Service Center
and sent National Institute of Animal Health.
Description of affected population: feeder cattle
Laboratory where diagnosis was made: Department of Exotic Diseases,
National Institute of Animal Health (Tokyo)
Diagnostic tests used: RT-PCR, ELISA for antibody detection
Causal agent/origin of lnfection: FMD virus type O is suspected by ELISA
for antibody detection.
Other epidemiological details: the origin of the infection is under
observation. The last case of FMD occurred in 1908 in Japan.
Control measures during reporting period: Stamping out of all cattle in the
infected farm followed by disinfection of the farm on 25 Mar 2000.
Movement control of animals and materials which may be contaminated are
carried out within the area with radius of 50 km from the infected farm.
Intensive surveillance has been taking place in the movement control area.
Last updated: 28 Mar 2000
--
Akira Goto
e-mail: dolphin@mail.ne.jp
